<div class="dablink">This article is about an abstract strategy game called <b>Hex</b>.  For the hexagonal map style popular in <a href="/wiki/Wargaming" title="Wargaming">wargaming</a>, see <a href="/wiki/Hex_map" title="Hex map">Hex map</a>.</div>
<p><b>Hex</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Board_game" title="Board game">board game</a> played on a <a href="/wiki/Hex_map" title="Hex map">hexagonal grid</a>, theoretically of any size and several possible shapes, but traditionally as an 11x11 rhombus. Other popular dimensions are 13x13 and 19x19 as a result of the game's relationship to the older game of <a href="/wiki/Go_(board_game)" title="Go (board game)" class="mw-redirect">Go</a>. According to the book <i><a href="/wiki/A_Beautiful_Mind_(book)" title="A Beautiful Mind (book)">A Beautiful Mind</a></i>, <a href="/wiki/John_Forbes_Nash" title="John Forbes Nash" class="mw-redirect">John Nash</a> (one of the game's inventors) advocated 14x14 as the optimal size.</p>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Hex_board_11x11.svg" class="image" title="11x11 Hex game board"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e9/Hex_board_11x11.svg/180px-Hex_board_11x11.svg.png" width="180" height="128" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Hex_board_11x11.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
11x11 Hex game board</div>
</div>
